<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the administration of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs on the course and results of parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of value added tax administration and the use of the VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) information system.</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so revenues from value added tax affect not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel auditing activities were mainly aimed at controlling the procedure of tax administrators when scrutinizing the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions carried out between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of VIES has enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of VAT payers in the various Member States of the European Union and on the commercial transactions carried out by those payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the data in the VIES system and the data in the VAT return filed by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and enable the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the parallel checks carried out consisted not only in the exchange of information on the procedures of the tax or tax authorities for administering value added tax, but in particular in the examination of the use of the VIES system in monitoring the exercise of the right to exemption from value added tax in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained during the implementation of parallel controls is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of other parallel controls in cooperation with the audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the administration of value added tax for the period from 1. 5. 2004 to 30. 6th 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of value added tax, (SK) Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) closed on 12. 9th 2005 Agreement on cooperation in control activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel auditing actions - Administration of Value Added Tax - included in the 2005 Audit Plan of the SAO, the Czech Republic under No. 05/19 and - Audit of the procedures of tax authorities in the administration, control and recovery of taxes from the added value and the fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between the member countries of the SAO - included in the Audit Plan of the SAO of the Slovak Republic under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel control actions carried out were coordinated controls.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated inspection was processed in accordance with European Enforcement Regulation 31 for INTOSAI inspection standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract concluded and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated audit was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious business transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "CR") and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SR").</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually agreed to provide each other with information from public sources, from the electronic system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests to verify commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the audit was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Ministry of Finance and 12 financial authorities: the Financial Authority in Mladá Boleslav, the Financial Authority in Kolín, the Financial Authority in Teplice, the Financial Authority in Karlovy Vary, the Financial Authority in Tábor, the Financial Authority Brno III, the Financial Authority in Znojmo, the Financial Authority in Zlín, the Financial Authority in Šumperk, the Financial Authority Ostrava I, the Financial Authority for Prague 7 and the Financial Authority for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the Exposures of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Tax Office Bratislava I, Tax Office Komárno, Tax Office Trenčín, Tax Office Prievidza, Tax Office Zvolen, Tax Office Dolný Kubín, Tax Office Košice II, Tax Office Košice V and Tax Office Michalovce.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of inspections:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel auditing actions was to examine the procedure of the tax authorities in administering value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "EU") and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, especially when controlling the application of the VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period of the coordinated audit covered the period from 1. 5. 2004 to 30. 6th 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions The electronic VIES system is in place in the EU Member States, which allows tax administrations to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT, and in the country of destination to check whether the customer has properly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralised within the EU, each Member State is developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit revealed differences in national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The recapitulative statements indicate the values of deliveries of goods to other EU Member States; the values of services rendered are not included in the recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, data from summary reports submitted by Czech payers are processed at the level of tax authorities, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States stated in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">Financial authorities transmit data from recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In the Slovak Republic, data from summary reports filed by Slovak taxpayers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and the value of supplies of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT tax returns, which makes it possible to compare the values stated in summary returns with the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and to identify any differences between them.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the values of goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported cumulatively on a common line of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in the Slovak Republic, the system does not allow for automatic identification of differences between the values of supplies of goods according to VAT tax returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the values of supplies of goods in VAT returns makes it possible to use the results of data comparisons to control the VAT exemption of supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">Delivered data from summary reports filed by payers in other EU Member States are processed on the CLO and compared with the value of acquisition of goods stated by payers from the Czech Republic or Slovakia in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the Slovak Republic, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax administrators themselves decide which cases of differences to check.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of supplies and acquisitions of goods must be verified by the tax administrators and submits a list of these cases to the locally competent tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that, for the most significant deviations, it is verified whether the VAT on the acquisition of the goods has been declared correctly.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some problems in the VAT administration system complications caused by different reporting of intra-Community transactions (i.e. supplies and acquisitions of goods by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">In the EU, recapitulative statements are submitted for each calendar quarter and the maximum time limit for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">The reduction of the period covered by recapitulative statements to one month, together with the reduction of the processing period, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">This would allow tax administrations to check more effectively whether VAT on intra-Community acquisitions has been declared in the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, filing VAT returns and recapitulative returns for the same tax period (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer declared identical values of supplies of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative return and the VAT tax return.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between the values of deliveries of goods reported by EU payers and the values of acquisitions of goods reported by payers from the Czech Republic or Slovakia were caused, among other things, by different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and acquisitions in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in summary reports or the reporting of intra-Community supplies in the supplier's summary report in a different quarter than intra-Community acquisitions in the purchaser's VAT tax return.</seg>
<seg id="50">Harmonising the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the tax administrations of individual Member States more effective.</seg>
<seg id="51">Cooperation between the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also aimed at examining selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, where there were doubts about their implementation or suspicions of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic found the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax subjects have declared in their VAT returns for the purpose of unduly obtaining excess VAT the carrying out of intra-Community transactions which have not actually taken place;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax subjects declared intra-Community supplies in carousel transactions where the value of supplies was deliberately reduced several times in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers declared in their VAT returns and recapitulative statements intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers have made intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to taxable persons who have not been registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers declared intra-Community supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than that declared by the purchasers of intra-Community acquisitions, in some cases VAT was declared at an incorrect amount.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the audit showed that VIES provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax administrations should pay particular attention to the rigorous examination of the differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the VIES data and to the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the accession of the Czech Republic and Slovakia to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1. 5. In 2004, the Czech Republic and Slovakia became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">Following EU accession, internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within the EU were abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">He was the VAT administrator until 30. 4th 2004 the relevant tax or tax office, with the exception of the import of goods and occasional bus transport in the Czech Republic, where the tax administrator was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as Act No. 235/2004 Coll.), or Act No. 222/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as Act No. 222/2004 Coll.), the administration of VAT on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU Member States has passed from customs offices to tax or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">In accordance with the provisions of Section 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., the delivery of goods in the Czech Republic means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">A supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is a supply of goods that have actually been dispatched or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">According to the provisions of Section 64 of Act No.235/2004 Coll., it is an exempt taxable supply with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are delivered to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">In accordance with the provisions of Section 8 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., the supply of tangible property in which the right of ownership is changed is considered a supply of goods in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods which are in the possession of the taxable person from the territory of the country to another Member State shall also be regarded as a supply of goods if those goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Under Article 43 of Law No 222/2004 Coll., the supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the customer is a person identified for VAT purposes in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">According to the provisions of Section 16 of Act No.235/2004 Coll., the acquisition of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods that are dispatched or transported to the customer by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer purchases goods at a price exclusive of VAT and is obliged to declare VAT in the Czech Republic in accordance with the provisions of Section 25 of Act No.235/2004 Coll., if the conditions set out in Section 73 of this Act are met, he is entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">In accordance with the provisions of Section 11 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., the acquisition of goods in the Czech Republic from another EU Member State means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of movable tangible property sent or transported to the purchaser by the supplier or purchaser or on their behalf to the Czech Republic from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">Tax liability in the Slovak Republic arises for the payer when acquiring goods in the Czech Republic from another Member State pursuant to the provisions of Section 20 of Act No.222/2004 Coll.</seg>
<seg id="78">Under the provisions of Section 49 of Act No 222/2004 Coll., the payer may deduct VAT if the tax is applied by him on the acquisition of goods within the country from another Member State in accordance with the provisions of Sections 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">According to the provisions of Section 17 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., or Section 45 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., a trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, where the subject of the trade is the supply of the same goods between these three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intra-Community transactions are supplies and acquisitions of goods made between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
