<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to the RES was set out in Art. 8 of this Regulation for 3 months.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions governing the admissibility of applications are laid down in Decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15. 11th 2004, which stipulates that, unless otherwise agreed by the Participating States, the SPA must cover commercial transactions of at least EUR 1 500 excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">Where the BOI relates to a commercial transaction with a value of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may refuse to reply in view of its workload.</seg>
<seg id="360">The procedure of the tax administration of the Czech Republic, including the indication of internal time limits set for processing at individual organizational levels, illustrates the following scheme.</seg>
<seg id="361">In Slovakia, the deadline for the processing of the LI by the tax authorities was set at 2 months so that the three-month deadline under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 could be met.</seg>
<seg id="362">MF CLO received from the Slovak Republic from 1. 5. 2004 to 30. 6th 2005 a total of 29 ZOIs and 3 SPIs.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 RES received, 26 (i.e. 89,7 %) dealt with within the deadline of 3 months and 3 (i.e. 10.3%) were discharged after this deadline.</seg>
<seg id="364">In the same period received DR CLO from the Czech Republic a total of 71 ŽOI and 7 SPI.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 RES received, 64 (i.e. 90,1%) completed within the deadline of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were dealt with after this deadline (for the other 2 cases it was not possible to determine the processing deadline from the materials transmitted).</seg>
<seg id="366">The following graph contains more detailed data on the time of processing of LIs received by MF CLO or DR CLO.</seg>
<seg id="367">The following table contains the reasons for sending the RES, as set out on the SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT and the use of the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States were examined, especially when controlling the exercise of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intra-Community transactions carried out between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="371">Examination of selected transactions revealed that, on the basis of an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries detected cases of companies carrying out fictitious intra-Community commercial transactions in order to obtain excessive VAT deductions, as well as cases where purchasers did not declare VAT on the correct amount of goods received.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audit also revealed differences in the processing and use of VIES data by tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also pointed to problems caused by different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and acquisitions of goods in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">Harmonising the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the tax administrations of individual Member States more effective.</seg>
<seg id="375">An examination of the procedures of the tax or tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system revealed that the tax or tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal authorisations.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that VIES did not provide up-to-date information in all cases on the supply of goods and on the validity of VAT registration of tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SA, processed before the start of the audit, with data processed after completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="378">It was clear from the comparison of these data that the SAO SR audit had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SH with incorrectly stated VAT numbers, but also on the reduction of the number of uncorrected errors in SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In case of discrepancies in the reported data, the SAO SR asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or to carry out tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic did not have such a possibility under the current legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the audit showed that VIES provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Given that there is still scope for tax evasion in this area, increased attention needs to be paid to intra-Community transactions when administering VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Chairman of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
