<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material provides an overview of the course and results of parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the area of value added tax and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the SAIs of both countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement on control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel control actions was chosen with regard to the fact that indirect taxes significantly contribute to the revenues of the state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The structure of value added tax, which allows the refund of excess deduction, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duties, in particular on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation through the illegal sale of these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, the VAT Working Group was created by the supreme audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union, in whose activities the supreme audit authorities of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in the joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax administration in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The acquired experience and knowledge will be used in the planned inspections of indirect taxes, aimed primarily at the involvement of the tax administrations of both countries in the VIES system, which allows the control of the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the audit of the administration of value added tax and excise duties for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1st Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Inspection number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the tax administrator's procedure for administering, controlling and enforcing value added tax and excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2. 2004 The Agreement on Cooperation in Audit Activities between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO SR) was concluded. The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel auditing operations "Value Added Tax and Excise Tax," included in the 2004 Audit Plan of the SAO under No. 04/07 and "Inspection of the Administrator's Procedure in Administration, Control and Recovery of Taxes from Added Value and Consumption Taxes," included in the Audit Plan of the SAO of the Slovak Republic under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract concluded and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, both parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from the files of tax entities maintained by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the parties could not obtain when controlling the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the respective State.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel from January to August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the audit was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of South Bohemia, Northeast Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected financial authorities: Financial Authority for Prague 1, Financial Authority for Prague 3, Financial Authority in České Budějovice, Financial Authority in Frýdek-Místek, Financial Authority in Hodonín, Financial Authority in Jihlava, Financial Authority in Kostelec nad Orlicí, Financial Authority in Kroměříž, Financial Authority in Písek, Financial Authority in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, Financial Authority in Ústí nad Orlicí, Financial Authority in Velké Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SR") was carried out by the Section of Tax and Customs Administration of the SAO SR in cooperation with the Expositions of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax Office Bratislava before selected tax entities, Tax Office Bratislava III, Tax Office Trnava, Tax Office Pú-chov, Tax Office Banská Bystrica I, Tax Office Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax Office Žilina I, Tax Office Žilina II, Tax Office Košice I and Tax Office Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the auditing activities was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of financial or tax authorities and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise taxes with a focus on the collection of these taxes in the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the relevant financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2nd Recap of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">Within the framework of international cooperation, the SAO handed over 22,206 items of the Uniform Declarations on Imports and Exports of Goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, while the SAO handed over 30,221 items of the JCD from the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was performed.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5,883 selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic, a total of 43% of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12 343 selected JCD entries from the SR Customs database, a total of 26% of the related JCD entries were attributed.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of the unassigned items of the JCD, a selection of files of tax entities was carried out at the tax or tax authorities, where the reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia and the financial or tax authorities, the implementation of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified on the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO of Slovakia carried out a joint pilot inspection at the Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma border crossing, during which both parties cooperated closely in verifying the correctness of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not detect any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation made it possible to examine trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both countries and highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">In the area of international cooperation, the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or other goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of an audit of the files of tax entities at selected tax or tax authorities, the SAO requested verification of the implementation of exports of goods declared for 40 JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 15,301,093 and the SAO requested verification of exports with a statistical value of CZK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic found the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="46">- errors in data entry in customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports/exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, there was no evidence of corresponding imports to Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there are reasonable grounds for suspecting fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of improperly claiming deductions of value added tax,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities failed to comply with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- Weaknesses have been identified in the activities of the tax authorities in administering value added tax and excise duties and in their interaction with customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duties, attention will continue to be paid to international trade in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activities of tax administrators when administering value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">Effective control of excise duties is based on control of the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information during import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3rd Description of the situation in the field of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax ("VAT") was levied by the tax or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out within the country and by the customs authorities on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">Tax revenues were determined at the tax or tax authorities by the difference between the collected own tax liability and the refunded excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">The VAT revenue at the customs offices was determined by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">In accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, the tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the tax deductions applied to the tax or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most tax authorities, the excess VAT deductions exceeded the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget revenues, as it accounted for approximately 31% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and approximately 42% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">Total VAT collection in the Czech Republic reached CZK 162.9 billion in 2003. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="63">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected a total of EUR 394.3 billion in VAT. CZK and refunded excess VAT deductions totalled CZK 231.4 billion. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="64">Total VAT collection in Slovakia amounted to EUR 83.8 billion in 2003. The Sk.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected EUR 187.0 billion in VAT. Sk and refunded excess VAT deductions totalled CZK 103.2 billion The Sk.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "SpD") was carried out by the relevant tax or tax authorities and, when importing products subject to the SpD, by customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of SpD in tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic was approximately 16% in 2003 and approximately 19% in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SpD collected in the Czech Republic by the financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to CZK 85.6 billion. CZK and reached CZK 38.0 billion in Slovakia. The Sk.</seg>
<seg id="70">4th Progress of control action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was carried out; in the second stage, the results of this comparison were used in the mutual verification of the implementation of selected trade transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and in inspections carried out on the territory of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel audits of VAT and SpD was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting took place at which, inter alia, a selection of commodities was agreed - types of goods which posed a significant risk in complying with customs and tax legislation: - alcohol and spirits, tariff headings 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff headings 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff headings 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff subheadings 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be carried out: a) from unassigned items determined by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, b) from entities carrying out imports and exports on a regular or one-off basis in large volumes, c) on the basis of findings from inspections carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the mechanism of mutual allocation of JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, the part of exports from the Czech Republic was compared with imports to Slovakia in 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol. or more; ethyl alcohol and other spirits, denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol. ; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unmanufactured tobacco; tobacco refuse,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars, cigarillos and cigarettes, of tobacco or of tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other manufactured tobacco and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and essences,</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception apparatus:</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception apparatus:</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with the apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling in subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">JCD items from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were mutually assigned on the basis of the conformity of individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle transporting freight, date of crossing the state border, customs tariff item, etc.). ).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are shown in the following tables and charts.</seg>
<seg id="92">The mutual allocation of individual imports and exports was hampered, among other things, by the fact that trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic, declared on one export JCD, were declared on the territory of the Slovak Republic on several import JCDs, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that influenced the success of the assignment were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as the time shift between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at audited financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">Furthermore, for the verification of business transactions reported in the VAT tax returns, some tax entities were selected for which data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot inspection at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing for the performance of pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="100">On the basis of a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the use of checklists has been introduced at border customs crossings between the Czech Republic and Slovakia since 1 June 1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate, as far as possible, customs and tax evasion, to ensure an overview of the movement of means of transport of goods of a commercial character in the customs area and to create conditions for mutual comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">A joint pilot inspection was carried out on 8. 3rd 2004 to 26. 3rd 2004 and aimed at verifying this customs control system.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of check sheets at the border crossing point Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the Audi A6, issuing the checklist and handing it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Parking in the marked sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs clearance in the clearance hall by the Police of the Czech Republic, the Police of the Slovak Republic, the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The check-in was confirmed by the various components by stamping the control sheet.</seg>
<seg id="108">(3) Presentation of the vehicle in the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the inspection sheet, JCD, or other documents to the customs administration employee - checking the execution of all prescribed acts and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Physical checks by the relevant services.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Attention: When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the vehicle was weighed directly by employees of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When importing goods into Slovakia, the vehicle was weighed by employees of an authorized legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were recorded in computer records after weighing.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is shown in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Control sheets and their registration Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="120">When exported from the Czech Republic to Slovakia, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these control sheets in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">From the number of 453 JCD items, the SAO of the Slovak Republic traced 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 items of the JCD were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the workers of the border customs crossing Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exported from Slovakia to the Czech Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">From a total of 339 items of the selected audit sample, the SAO, in cooperation with the border customs crossing staff of Starý Hrozenkov, assigned the corresponding registration numbers of the control sheets to 295 items of the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in their records by employees of the border customs crossing Drietoma and the export of goods from Slovakia to the Czech Republic was confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The SAO and SAO SR did not detect any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified on the basis of customs administrations and financial or tax authorities in the territory of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="130">For selected tax subjects, the following were verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of legal conditions for application of VAT deduction on import, refund of excess VAT deduction and application of VAT exemption on export.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of commercial transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1st The SAO SR requested verification of the implementation of alcohol exports with a statistical value of 56,989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified the corresponding import in the customs database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of CZK 42,624.</seg>
<seg id="136">2nd The company engaged in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories applied an excess VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in the VAT return for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to audit reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCDs (16 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO SR identified 3 corresponding import JCDs (17 items) with a statistical value of 1 724 321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">The VAT was paid in Slovakia to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="140">3rd In 2002, the company, which mainly traded in optical instruments, claimed a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4 1 36 000 higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO SR found that this JCD corresponds to import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9,653,827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">The VAT was paid in Slovakia to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="144">4th A company engaged, inter alia, in the purchase of goods for resale and sale did not record any export of goods in the VAT returns submitted in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of goods exports totalled CZK 3,439,888 in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO SR identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) with a statistical value of 1,012,656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The audit of the SAO SR at the relevant tax office proved the realization of the declared imports and the payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. In 2002, the company, whose subject of business was, inter alia, the purchase of goods for resale and the sale, manufacture, installation and repair of electrical machinery and appliances, reported in its VAT returns the export of goods worth CZK 12,966,706.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the total value of exports amounted to CZK 14,474,381 in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified in the customs database SR 13 JCDs (50 items) with a statistical value of 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the Slovak customs database, it was not possible to identify the corresponding import JCD for 4 export JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax office in Slovakia verified these imports with the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity, listed on the JCD as an importer to Slovakia, stated in the minutes of the local investigation that it had not made imports declared on the Czech export JCDs.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO therefore asked the local tax authority to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate income tax for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">6th According to the Czech Customs Database, the company engaged in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco labels with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 in 2002 and CZK 12,228,545 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="158">In the VAT returns, the company did not report any exports in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected for verification 5 export JCDs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">For 4 export JCDs (4 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,246,860, the SAO SR identified in the customs database SR 7 JCDs (7 items) with a statistical value of Sk 2,919,514.</seg>
<seg id="161">It was not possible to assign the corresponding import to the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 224,738 in the Slovak customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7th The software company did not declare exports of goods in the VAT returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of goods exports in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the customs database of the Slovak Republic, the SAO of the Slovak Republic identified 8 JCDs (8 items) with a statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">It was not possible to assign the corresponding import to the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of 68 286 CZK in the Slovak customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it was not possible to identify in the Slovak customs database the corresponding imports for 6 JCDs with a statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- for 2 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of CZK 293,024, the corresponding import JCD could not be identified in the customs database of the Slovak Republic (see points 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to some error in entering data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify some registered imports, e.g. in cases where the importer's name was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (TIN).</seg>
<seg id="171">Therefore, it cannot be established with certainty that these exports were not made.</seg>
<seg id="172">- for 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia with a statistical value of CZK 399,776 were not proven (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there is reason to suspect the fictitious export of goods for the purpose of improperly claiming a VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the control of selected financial or tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in the import and export of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between financial and customs authorities, the files of tax entities were selected at the audited financial and tax authorities according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. Tax subjects were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia: a) with the highest volume of imports, b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. tax entities were selected from the records of the tax or tax authorities according to the amount of: a) applied VAT deductions on import, b) applied excessive VAT deductions, c) claim for SpD refund, d) applied VAT exemption on export,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. taxable persons subject to a tax audit.</seg>
<seg id="180">Sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic of risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Control of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="184">At the audited financial offices, the SAO focused mainly on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the tax authorities for verifying the correctness of the VAT declared,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the JCD database at tax offices with a focus on comparing the declared value, applying the correct VAT rate following the customs classification of goods or services, or comparison of data on JCD and attached invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- comparison of data from VAT returns on transactions made and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at tax offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- the method of verifying the right to VAT exemption when exporting goods or services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax offices contained only records of those imports and exports for which tax entities were obliged to declare imports or exports in the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited tax authorities scrutinized the files of tax entities that reported imports in the total amount of CZK 60,396,379 thousand and the corresponding VAT in the total amount of CZK 12,644,052 thousand in VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of tax entities reporting exports totalling CZK 47,323,111,000 in the tax returns for 2002 and 2003 were scrutinized.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the tax entities for which imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were examined carried out in 2002 and 2003 imports into the Czech Republic from Slovakia with a total VAT base of CZK 3,759,352,000, VAT of CZK 767,607,000 and exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090,000.</seg>
<seg id="195">The observed differences between records in the JCD database at financial offices and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items that were missing from the customs database of the Czech Republic were requested directly from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- for JCD items that were missing from the IRS database, it was verified that they were not cancelled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items where different values were found between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of financial authorities, the relevant JCD was requested from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form, including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The audit revealed that the JCD database at financial offices did not contain, for example, records of import JCDs with a total VAT value of CZK 3,622,000 and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359,000.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences found</seg>
<seg id="201">A comparison of the JCD database at the tax authorities and the cumulative tax liabilities for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT tax returns of a selected sample of tax subjects revealed the following differences:</seg>
<seg id="202">Differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time lag between the realisation of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct VAT charged on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The tax subject could exercise the right of deduction for the importation of goods within 3 years of the end of the tax period in which the goods were placed under the relevant procedure or, in the case of the temporary importation procedure, within 3 years of the end of the tax period in which the procedure ended.</seg>
<seg id="205">- Time difference between the realization of the export and the moment when the tax subject received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The tax subject was obliged to include data on realized exports exempt from the obligation to apply output tax in the VAT tax return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods left the country, if he also had a tax document, which was JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure of taxpayers to comply with their obligations when reporting imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax subjects did not provide correct data on imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">As tax subjects did not have to attach lists of JCDs to the submitted VAT returns, the control of the right to deduct VAT or the exemption from VAT by the tax authorities was made more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Interaction between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the audited period, import or export duties and VAT were reimbursed or remitted on the basis of customs decisions.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax subjects were required by law to reduce the previously claimed right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax refunded by the customs office in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the sending of information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT from customs offices to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax offices received this information, but irregularly or with significant time delays and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax office did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information about changes in the amount of duty and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data necessary to check the fulfilment of the legal obligation of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs authorities refunded VAT in the amount of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 in the amount of more than CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit pointed to persistent shortcomings in the activities of tax administrators, some systemic errors in the cooperation of tax authorities with customs authorities and non-fulfilment of some obligations of payers filing VAT and SpD tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="219">Deficiencies in the administration of VAT and SpD were found in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">a) in the event of cancellation of VAT registrations, the fulfilment of the obligation of payers to pay VAT on the registered business assets, or which should have been registered on the date of cancellation of the registration, in respect of which the payer applied the tax deduction, was verified only sporadically,</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities did not consistently make use of the possibility of carrying out a tax audit or on-the-spot investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">This led in some cases to insufficient verification of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">c) official records and minutes of the oral hearing did not contain all the necessary data demonstrating the legitimacy of the excessive VAT deductions applied,</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities have not sufficiently verified the imports and exports declared in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Control of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For a selected sample, the SAO verified or the tax office carried out a tax audit for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analyzing the submitted tax returns and applications for tax refunds at selected tax entities, the SAO SR asked the tax office to secure the relevant JCDs documenting import and export, invoices and tax payment documents.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO scrutinized whether the submitted JCDs registered in the customs database of imports and exports and the fulfilment of decisive facts and legal conditions in the application of the input tax deduction in respect of imports, in the refund of excess VAT deduction, in the application of export tax exemption and in the refund of SpD.</seg>
<seg id="230">At 10 audited tax offices, the SAO verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the structure according to the number of JCD items and the sum of statistical values given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports with a statistical value of 856.2 million Sk were audited, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic into SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were audited in the total statistical value of 176 million Sk, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from Slovakia to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">Furthermore, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white technology, packaging technology and software) from EU countries to Slovakia were audited with a total statistical value of 532.8 million Sk.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Interaction between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO SR found discrepancies between the data registered in the Slovak customs database and the data reported in specific VAT tax returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax subjects (natural persons) declared in their tax returns imports of goods with a total value of SKK 1 589 261, on the basis of which they claimed a refund of excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">During local investigations carried out on the initiative of the SAO SR, tax entities were unable to prove to the tax office the legitimacy of applying input tax with relevant documents on importation and VAT payment,</seg>
<seg id="238">- tax entity (s.r. (o.) in the tax return for the tax period January 2003 declared the received taxable supply in the value of SKU 77 167 576, the export of goods in the value of SKU 18 006 041 and claimed an excess VAT deduction in the amount of SKU 17 157 101.</seg>
<seg id="239">It is apparent from the VAT returns submitted for 2003 that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports, amounting to SKU 59 161 535, which arose in January 2003, was not corrected during the whole of 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above-mentioned cases, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the excessive VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s.r. (o.) for the tax period January to June 2002, declared in the VAT tax returns the export of goods with a total value of SKK 87,199.</seg>
<seg id="242">Verification in the Slovak customs database revealed that the tax subject carried out an export with a statistical value of 296 747 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="243">The tax office carried out a number of on-the-spot investigations at the company's headquarters, finding that the company's manager (a UK citizen) had departed and the company had left the rented premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the SAO audit, the tax administrator filed a notice with the criminal authorities on suspicion of committing the crime of non-payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of the audit at selected tax offices, the SAO of the Slovak Republic states that the biggest problems in the management and control of VAT and SpD occurred mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- not making use of the possibility to carry out a VAT tax audit on problematic tax subjects, in particular in cases of application of a high value of excess VAT;</seg>
<seg id="247">- tax audit reports did not include an inventory of audited documents</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient verification of declared imports and exports of goods in tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy procedures for tax administrations to take decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, including the loss of the right to impose penalties;</seg>
<seg id="251">- failure to comply with legal conditions when granting tax deferrals,</seg>
<seg id="252">- non-compensation of VAT arrears by the refund deadline,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">On the basis of the shortcomings detected by the audit, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of VAT with a focus on the legitimacy of excessive VAT deductions applied to 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">At all audited tax offices, measures were taken to eliminate the deficiencies detected by the audit, the fulfilment of which will be monitored and audited by the SAO of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="256">6th Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation made it possible to examine trade transactions carried out between trading partners from both countries and highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The audit also revealed persistent shortcomings in the fulfilment of obligations of VAT and SpD payers, in the activities of tax or tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs authorities, which ultimately reduced the effectiveness and efficiency of tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have at their disposal basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic as part of the tax information system. In Slovakia, there is no similar system for the transmission of information on imports and exports of goods between customs and tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the administration of VAT and SpD was not the same in view of the different legal regulations and conditions in the territory of both States.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained from the Czech Customs Administration and from documents available at audited financial offices. The SAO audited commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel audits carried out in the area of VAT and SpD assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the period before accession to the European Union and pointed out the necessity of further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further deepened in the control of the activities of the tax or tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called summary report.</seg>
<seg id="266">This declaration must be submitted by all VAT payers who have made a supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are obliged to enter data from summary reports into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System) system, to which tax administrators from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">The tax or tax authorities then have the opportunity to compare these data with the data contained in the submitted VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is also used to verify the validity of the VAT registration number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the validity of the VAT exemption applied when goods are delivered to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel audits showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these audits will be confronted with the results of the upcoming audits, which will focus, among other things, on the verification of the VIES system, which is supposed to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-Community supplies."</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SPD for budgetary revenues, control activities should focus primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion in indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the Chairman of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
