<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of inspections in asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and funds earmarked for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Control action No. 04/23 - State property and funds earmarked for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="4">Inspection action No. 15/2004 - Inspection of the economy with the property of the state and financial resources intended for the provision of asylum and temporary refuge for foreigners in Slovakia"</seg>
<seg id="5">1st Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena that has a global character and has become an inseparable part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">In particular, it is caused by the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, in particular for racial, religious, national, political reasons, as well as from the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to gain asylum and integration into society, especially in some of Europe's advanced democratic countries.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group includes foreigners whose reason for migration is unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the Geneva Agreement of 1951 and the New York Protocol of 1967 relating to the Status of Refugees, by which the governments of the signatory countries undertook to apply them in their foreign-policy orientation, brought about the establishment of specific principles for refugee assistance.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federal Republics ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with adopted international documents and confirmed their binding force within the framework of national legislation by means of a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have also enshrined the provision of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are contained in the joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">Cooperation between the Supreme Audit Institutions of both countries was implemented on the basis of the "Contract on Cooperation in Audit Activities" (hereinafter referred to as the "Contract") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Treaty, both Parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing asylum procedures in the State of the other Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem areas and to highlight the consequences for population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted in harmonising the programme of control actions, exchanging information to the extent provided for by the Treaty and drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the controls.</seg>
<seg id="20">During the first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4. to 7.4.2004, the same areas of audited issues and control procedures during the preparation of auditing events were determined.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place from 28.6. to 30.6. 2004, the common points for the control action programme were clarified.</seg>
<seg id="22">During the third joint meeting, which took place during the auditing operation from 8.11. to 10.11.2004, the experience of the ongoing audits was exchanged.</seg>
<seg id="23">The modalities of the control outputs have been specified and the structure and content of the joint final report, which was drawn up between 14.2. and 17.2. 2005 at the last joint meeting.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audits were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the audit was carried out by auditors from the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited bodies were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "MoI') and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "SUZ').</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic carried out an inspection of the section of defense, interior and štátnych úradov.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migration Office of the Ministry of Interior of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "MÚ").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2001, 2002 and 2003 (hereinafter referred to as the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data covering a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2nd Recap of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Assessment of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subjects of the parallel checks were: - the asylum process, - asylum facilities, - the management of funds and state property, - the internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic took place in the phase of preparation and implementation of audit actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange allowed for a more thorough evaluation of the submitted documents, to analyse the causes of the identified differences in the security of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">In this way, it was possible to focus on the decisive problems affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this had a positive impact on the quality of the implementation of the control activity.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of the results of the audit</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with the documents of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "EU") was the subject of evaluation reports by the European Commission on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">Legislation in this area continues to be adopted after the accession of both countries to the EU with a view to further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has steadily increased, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security for asylum seekers within the meaning of international agreements.</seg>
<seg id="44">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget of both countries is mainly influenced by the number of applicants, the length of the asylum procedure until asylum is granted or refused, as well as the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some levies collected is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic set up asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of the asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="48">In asylum facilities, asylum seekers are provided with accommodation, food, health care and basic material equipment and sanitary supplies during their stay.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organized as part of leisure activities and the conditions for cultural and sporting activities are created for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, and in the Czech Republic also integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost of one day of stay depends on the occupancy and facilities of the centre and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is broadly stable.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1 000 jobs in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, whose increasing numbers are expected to continue in the coming years in the context of the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on the provision of services. Crucial expenditure under this heading was the cost of lodging and boarding applicants in asylum facilities operated under contract, the cost of health care provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service to protect asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also accounted for a significant share of total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the migration policy and asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures addressing legitimate demands related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services accounted for the bulk of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings that did not have a major impact on the financial and state property management.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were shortcomings in particular in the area of the use of state budget funds, contrary to the purpose for which they were designated by the Act on the State Budget, when current expenditures were used to cover actions in the nature of technical appreciation of long-term tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The law on accounting in the area of inventory and non-compliance with the chart of accounts was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor shortcomings were also found in the handling of state property when it was left to another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes in the Land Registry data violated the Land Registry Act and the Waste Act was violated by leaving the waste for disposal to a person who was not authorized to handle the waste.</seg>
<seg id="64">Furthermore, in the Slovak Republic, weaknesses were found in the provision of disproportionately high advances for the purchase of electricity and natural gas, in public procurement and in the management of state property when its records were not sufficiently secured and the method of liquidating unnecessary assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system was ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the generally binding legislation in force governing the method of financial control.</seg>
<seg id="66">No deficiencies were found in the written documentation submitted.</seg>
<seg id="67">Despite some shortcomings, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic positively evaluate the progress of SUZ and MÚ in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the findings obtained during the audit, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic state that despite a significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the respective organizational units of both countries have managed the tasks associated with the care of asylum seekers to an appropriate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is operational and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the audit were discussed with the interested statutory representatives of the relevant state organizational units on both the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the audit, we recommend that the positive methodological experience from the audit be used in other joint audit actions within the framework of international cooperation of SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="72">3rd Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and the 1967 New York Protocol).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legal regulation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., on Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic it is from 1. 1st 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and on Amendment to Act No. 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended five times (by Act No. 2/2002 Coll., Act No. 217/2002 Coll., Act No. 320/2002 Coll., Act No. 519/2002 Coll. and Act No. 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, are currently in the legislative process and the adoption of other amendments will be tied to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of the creation of Act No.325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, the area of asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and asylum documents were political documents in their binding nature.</seg>
<seg id="79">Already during the adoption of this law, efforts were made to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">An important change for asylum policy within the EU was the transfer of asylum issues from the 3rd to the 1st pillar, when the right of asylum became part of Community law from 1 May. 1999 under the Treaty of Amsterdam.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift has also necessitated the development of appropriate legislation, i.e. the creation of legal instruments with appropriate legal force.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents has been the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community regulations in the field of asylum were adopted shortly before or after the Czech Republic joined the EU and their transposition period at the time of the Supreme Audit Office audit, the Czech Republic has not yet expired.</seg>
<seg id="84">Once they have been transposed into Czech law, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission how it has transposed them.</seg>
