<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel audits of expenditures on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of the trans-European transport networks, it would be difficult to imagine a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating the conditions for rapid, safe, reliable and inexpensive transport of people and freight is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">This is a very demanding task, both organisationally and technically and financially.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often find it difficult to compromise with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Construction of transport infrastructure, also thanks to the necessary measures in favour of the environment, is costly.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considered procedures and decision-making by the state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport constructions can bring significant savings in public financial resources that can be used in other ways for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the roles of audit institutions is to actively seek out deficiencies that have led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditures on transport infrastructure constructions.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit institutions should not only draw the public administration's attention to the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures to improve the situation, for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">The two supreme audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as Germany and the Czech Republic) the Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as "BRH") and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as "SAO") carried out parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (the D8 motorway in the Czech Republic and the A17 motorway in Germany) in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="14">The highways are connected by a border bridge co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to the cooperation with the SAO, the BRH was able to carry out a thorough audit of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">On the basis of close cooperation with the BRH, the SAO obtained for comparative purposes the necessary data on the level of German bridge and tunnel costs.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">The </seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and to ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, as a result, RMD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit work, the prices of bridges on the D8 and A17 motorways were compared on the basis of a conversion per m2 of the bridge structure area.</seg>
<seg id="24">The statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per m2 of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">Analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in a group of large bridges with a length of over 100 meters.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase was also attributable to the delay in the contract procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the tunnel construction costs, the auditors found that the tunnel prices on the D8 motorway were significantly higher than those of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">The BRH and the SAO now have a database of bridge and tunnel prices on which they will be able to rely in future efficiency checks of funds used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both audit institutions recommend: standardization of bridge constructions and the use of coupled steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where prestressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The main features of the cooperation were its team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel check, auditors shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report informs on the course and results of parallel audits of funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The audits focused on economy, efficiency and effectiveness of incurred expenses.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel audits were carried out by the BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
