<p>
<seg id="1">Public works procurement and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel audit carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and private spheres.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the State is to use public resources as efficiently and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor for the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In its rules, the EU has set thresholds above which the contracting authority must comply with certain requirements to ensure a broad and unrestricted competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts below EU thresholds, the regulation of their award remains a matter for individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption with a consequent high potential for damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair advantage (corruption prevention).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits in the area of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The audits included the awarding of contracts below European thresholds in order to cover the area of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two SAIs are summarised in a joint report addressed, inter alia, to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and institutions audited</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH evaluation is based on area-based inspections of the above-mentioned areas carried out at the German building administrations responsible for federal transport and land constructions between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, highway construction and large-scale building construction projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH included findings from past audits in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's evaluation is based on audits carried out between 2008 and 2012, which focused on road constructions, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other constructions in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal public procurement is mostly carried out by the Land Building Administrations.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, state institutions for road and rail construction are responsible for awarding public contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of building construction, public procurement is carried out by the beneficiaries of the budget.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used in the various stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation should take into account the differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and subordinate standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany are governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts .</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details concerning the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called federal government procurement manuals, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail in the light of legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation concerning contracts with a value above and below European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Procurement law underwent substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up scope for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As regards European procurement procedures, open and restricted procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European threshold are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, restricted call for competition, negotiated procedure), but these are practically identical to the above-mentioned conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and when calling for competition, any candidate may submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is mainly achieved by dividing the total public contract into commercially specific lots and subdividing it into subcontracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">By awarding contracts divided into these lots, as many candidates as possible are given a chance to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested instruments for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, it is necessary to apply the conditions of European procedures also in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified below-threshold procedure, where the contracting authority may use less onerous procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between an open procedure and a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total volume of public works contracts awarded by contracting entities and share of each type of procedure in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction works in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK, of which CZK 1 138 billion. CZK (15%) accounted for the share of public contracts, which in addition to contracts awarded by the federal government included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of federal road and land construction projects (excluding railway and water construction) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal contracts for land works and transport works was as follows: 80.7 % open procedures and calls for tender; 12.7 % restricted procedures and calls for tender;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% negotiated procedures and direct procurement; 33.2% is the proportion of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached CZK 118.6 billion in 2011. CZK , which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009 it amounted to EUR 194.0 billion. CZK, which was 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of types of procurement procedures in 2011: 65,1 % open procedures; 14,3 % restricted procedures; 9,5 % negotiated procedures; 8,4 % simplified procedures for below-threshold contracts; 2,7 % other procedures.</seg>
<seg id="59">These figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel controls in both countries focused on a substantial part of public procurement procedures; the prevention of corruption, which must always be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open importance. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and the BRH carried out parallel audits of European public works contracts with an emphasis on preventing corruption in their respective countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The audits focused on the comparison of legal regulations in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public contracts in the field of land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="64">The following are the key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national laws of both countries (points 1. and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Preventing corruption is not only an objective of the EU directive, but of the two countries" national procurement rules, which differ partly in focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement to be met by the tender documents is the inclusion of all the information needed for the preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, insufficient definition of the subject matter of the contract is a problem.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, the division of contracts into lots is required wherever possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement is complied with in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO audits proved that in the Czech Republic, public works in the field of road construction are awarded without being divided into parts or subdivided, but only into very significant parts. This method may distort competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Such restrictions on market potential may result in significant cost increases and risk improper price negotiations and impermissible agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting entities, under certain conditions, to additionally award additional works if this need arises after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for correct determination of the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, according to the applicable regulations, contracting entities are free to designate one of the open procurement procedures, namely the open procedure or the restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German procurement and budget law rules enshrine the primacy of open procedures for both European and national tenders, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a wider range of candidates to submit bids and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it more difficult to negotiate prices illegally between candidates.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">For large contracts with an estimated total price reaching or exceeding the thresholds set by the EU, the contracting authorities audited have always launched a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">Correct determination of the expected value of the contract plays a very important role in determining the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to objectively determine the price of public works, in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective instrument.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are only used in the field of road construction but are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish preliminary information and a contract notice in order to strengthen competition by allowing candidates to prepare themselves in good time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">There is a greater risk of manipulation when selecting candidates to participate in a restricted procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">Beyond EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries should rotate as often as possible the candidates they invite to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are partly very detailed requirements to prevent the risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the contracting authorities audited did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (paragraph 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting entities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between those candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must, as far as possible, be prevented from restricting competition by means of illegal agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the German contracting authorities audited did not meet this requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality requirements for tenders are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (paragraph 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of bids is procedurally regulated in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive but have not always been respected by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities transmitted their tenders to third parties for inspection without their prior assessment, without adequately documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The tenders were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (section 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">For reasons of legal protection enterprises are to be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule is also designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The procurement documentation of the audited contracting authorities in both countries was not always complete or fully credible.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level were not always properly respected in the minutes of the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="113">Moreover, some of the weaknesses identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly complied with their reporting obligations (paragraph 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of guiding principles of European procurement law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts with a view to ensuring the free movement of goods and services and a Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to review procedures for the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (the Remedies Directive), which were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general EU procurement principles include in particular: the requirement for a competitive environment; the requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; the requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include In addition, the Directive on the coordination of public procurement procedures includes provisions for construction projects with a total estimated value of €5 million or more.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: the content of the specifications; the type of procurement procedure used; the publication of certain information before, during and after the procedure; compliance with the deadline for receipt of tenders; the qualification requirements that may be required of tenderers; the criteria for selecting the most suitable tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of tenderers is governed by the Remedies Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of the procurement right, tenderers may have the contracting authority's decision reviewed in accordance with the review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In neither country is there a legal definition of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is generally understood as the abuse of a personal (confidential) position for one's own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is encouraged by the beneficiaries.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">Overall corruption-related damage is estimated to amount to 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU area, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved, agreements restricting competition or allowing unfair conduct may undermine confidence in the integrity, capability and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">This is why preventing corruption is a key task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">In particular, practices and procedures need to be checked in areas particularly susceptible to corruption in order to take adequate measures to prevent corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Taking preventive measures and carrying out effective checks can substantially reduce the vulnerability of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">Public works procurement is generally considered to be an area particularly vulnerable to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures in the field of prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable under criminal and labour law, in particular active and passive bribery, receiving and offering significant benefits.</seg>
<seg id="139">The German federal government has issued a manual with recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the federal administration, according to which the following principles are applied throughout the procurement process outside the risk analysis: the priority of open procurement; the principle of multiple control and transparent decision-making; the separation of the planning, procurement and accounting phases; accurate and complete procurement documentation.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other preventive measures against corruption have become part of the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the relevant Federal Ministry of Information Technology introduced a system to monitor procurement for the construction of federal roads.</seg>
<seg id="142">With this system, data such as estimated costs, the total value of the contract and the involvement of private design offices can be fully recorded and analysed in order to identify any discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is prosecuted under criminal law, including on the level of labour and civil law.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirement for transparency, equal treatment and non-discrimination throughout the procurement process (preparation and implementation) is the most important part of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">Anti-corruption measures in this area were set out by the government in the "Government Anti-Corruption Strategy 2011-2012," which was updated for 2013 and 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Part of these measures was incorporated into the Public Procurement Act and related implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation contains the following basic provisions: reduction of the thresholds for small-scale contracts; obligation of prior notification by the contracting authority, including the reasons for the contract; prohibition of limiting the number of tenderers in the restricted procedure and abolition of the general possibility to limit the number of tenderers by drawing lots; obligation to publish contracts, including annexes; obligation to publish actual and lists of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Results of inspections relating to subsequent stages of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Tender documents</seg>
<seg id="150">The specifications shall contain all the information necessary to enable tenderers to prepare their tenders in an appropriate manner.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the documentation must make it possible to process the tender price.</seg>
<seg id="152">For this to be possible, candidates must not be exposed to risks which they could not have anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="153">The specifications shall include, in particular, the specifications, the requirements for demonstrating the qualifications of the tenderers and the criteria for selecting the most advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="154">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="155">European law contains, in particular, requirements concerning technical specifications.</seg>
