<seg id="418">Conclusions and recommendations/summary</seg>
<seg id="419">A two-stage information process with prior information and the publication of a notice of initiation is an important tool for meeting the requirements of transparency and strengthening the competitive environment in European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="420">By extending the obligation to publish preliminary information in the Czech Republic also for national procurement procedures and by strengthening this obligation in Germany for restricted procedures, both countries have increased the transparency of procurement procedures and improved the competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="421">Selection of candidates in restricted procurement procedures</seg>
<seg id="422">Unlike an open procedure, restricted procurement procedures do not allow all potential interested tenderers to participate.</seg>
<seg id="423">In restricted procedures, the procuring entity shall first select potential suppliers to be asked to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="424">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="425">EU provisions allow limiting the number of candidates in European restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="426">However, the restricted procedure requires at least five tenderers to be invited to submit a tender and, in the case of a negotiated procedure with publication, at least three potential tenderers must be invited.</seg>
<seg id="427">In any event, the number of candidates invited must be sufficiently large to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="428">The selection criteria shall be objective and non-discriminatory and shall be published in advance.</seg>
<seg id="429">The selection of potential candidates to be invited is highly susceptible to manipulation, e.g. the preferences of some of them.</seg>
<seg id="430">Reducing competition to a few bidders may ease their collusion.</seg>
<seg id="431">This has a negative impact on the outcome of the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="432">Therefore, the contracting authority must take measures to prevent manipulation and ensure that it has effective control so that the procedure is transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="433">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="434">Identical or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="435">The provisions for selecting candidates are similar in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="436">In addition to the requirements of the European Directive, contracting entities should replace the tenderers they invite to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="437">Nor is it permissible to restrict competition from a regional point of view.</seg>
<seg id="438">Contracting entities must document and justify the selection of tenderers and the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="439">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="440">In Germany, at least three candidates are required to be invited in the restricted procedure and several suitable candidates in the negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="441">With the exception of two cases, the new Czech regulations do not allow limiting the number of candidates addressed in the case of a restricted and negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="442">In Germany, the "four-eyes principle" must be respected when selecting candidates.</seg>
<seg id="443">While one worker proposes a list of candidates, another must substantially modify the list, e.g. by deleting the proposed candidate or by installing another.</seg>
<seg id="444">This is intended to avoid a situation in which an individual can definitively determine the pool of candidates to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="445">In the absence of such a provision, far-reaching illegal collusion between the parties is possible.</seg>
<seg id="446">The list of tenderers invited to submit a tender must be confidential and must not be divulged.</seg>
<seg id="447">Authorised independent experts are also obliged to do so.</seg>
<seg id="448">In the Czech Republic, there is no similar measure or measure for the confidential treatment of the list of candidates.</seg>
<seg id="449">Under the German provisions, they may not designate candidates from an external company, but may submit proposals to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="450">There is no similar requirement in the Czech Republic.</seg>
