<seg id="597">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="598">EU law sets out the process of assessing and evaluating bids in several steps:</seg>
<seg id="599">The first step is to check the suitability of candidates.</seg>
<seg id="600">They must be in a good economic and financial position and have the requisite professional and technical knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="601">Candidates who have ever been finally convicted of bribery or fraud must always be excluded from procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="602">Tenders from candidates who have not been eliminated must be evaluated for numerical accuracy, technical suitability and value for money on the basis of previously published award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The contracting authority must identify the most economically advantageous tender and in particular examine all significantly low price offers.</seg>
<seg id="604">Review and evaluation is particularly sensitive and prone to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, tenderers may be excluded without a legitimate reason, or tenders that do not meet the requirements may be retained in competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">The outcome of the evaluation may be improperly influenced by the preference or disadvantage of a tenderer, thereby preventing the selection of the most economically advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="607">The contracting authority must therefore take special precautions when selecting the persons involved in the process and must ensure that they meet the requirements of good repute and technical knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="608">They also need to make sure that the whole process and the decisions taken are transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="609">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Identical or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="611">In line with EU requirements, the relevant provisions in both countries require the examination and evaluation of bids in stages.</seg>
<seg id="612">The requirements for demonstrating the suitability of tenderers, the evaluation criteria and their weightings set out in the notice or in the tender dossier shall not be altered during the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="613">The criteria laid down for assessing the suitability of candidates may no longer be applied.</seg>
<seg id="614">A further evaluation may only be carried out on the basis of the evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The tenders submitted must first be examined from a formal point of view to ensure that they are complete or do not contain suspicious elements which might encourage manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="616">If tenderers are excluded from further examination and evaluation of the tenders submitted by them, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="617">Where the evaluation of tenders results in the finding of an unreasonably low tender price, the tenderer concerned must be given the opportunity to comment on the situation before any elimination of its tender.</seg>
<seg id="618">The reasons for the decision shall be transparently documented.</seg>
<seg id="619">Different provisions</seg>
