<seg id="648">Key control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRHs</seg>
<seg id="650">Examination of suitability and award criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of some self-employed recommendations from potential suppliers, the contracting authorities themselves did not check the suitability of the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="653">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some cases, insufficient documentation was provided on whether the contracting entity had taken into account all the published evaluation criteria when making the choice or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested parties and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting entities used the services of unauthorised persons, such as self-employed persons or employees of building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were integrated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be performed exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">The contracting authorities tried to justify this fact by their insufficient human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, they used self-employed professionals to examine the offers of services of persons who were not formally bound to respect the confidentiality of tenders and to perform their obligations under the contract with due diligence.</seg>
<seg id="660">As regards contracting authorities, there was generally no conclusive evidence as to whether tenders in the custody of self-employed professionals were available only to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Examination and mathematical control of tenders</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting entities handed over open envelopes for further examination to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed examination of tenders and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of those examinations.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intention to manipulate, third parties could make changes to tenders which could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">Examination of the documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the tenders were not adequately identified or where information on prices and products was missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A sample check by one contracting authority revealed that in 75% of procurement procedures, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10% from the pre-estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One in 20 procurement procedures was cancelled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was a lack of evidence or sufficient documentation of the screening of tenders or of discussions with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases, detailed information was also missing, e.g. on the unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or increases in material costs were often cited as reasons for the deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">The contracting entities argued that it was difficult to identify and demonstrate countervailing prices.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders, made by an entity outside the circle of ordinary contracting authorities, a 66% lower price was offered compared to the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="673">Data on closer examination of cost or identification of the reasons for deviations were not recorded.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority found no indication of price dumping by the tenderer to which the contract might have been awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clarified whether the original cost estimate was inflated or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">Subsequently, the contracting authority rated the tenderer as a "low-cost company" which was unable to meet either the qualitative requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35% higher than the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the tendering procedure, arguing that the tenderer could be presumed not to have based its pricing on unreasonably high costs.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspected irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">Two cases of irregularities were found in one contracting entity and they were reported to the firm responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one call for tenders, two tenderers submitted tenders containing identical price calculations, which prompted the contracting authority to exclude both tenders.</seg>
<seg id="682">The checks did not reveal any substantial deficiencies in the application of other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Verification of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">For many construction projects, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting entities did not exclude tenderers from participating in the procurement procedure even though they did not meet the requirements of the contracting authority specified in the specifications, or did not substantiate qualifications to the required extent, or, conversely, one contracting authority failed to substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of a candidate who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Rating</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a waste water treatment plant, the various evaluation criteria of the tendering procedure were imposed on the contractor, but the contracting authority did not comply with them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For the rail infrastructure development action, the weightings of the evaluation criteria were not set at the start of the procedure when the contract was awarded, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the evaluation of the criterion "reduced construction time" was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For the second and third place bidders, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater reduction in construction time than indicated in their bids.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of reasons for candidate selection</seg>
<seg id="692">In the case of three actions connected with housing support, the contracting authority did not demonstrate on the basis of which criteria it assessed the accepted bids and how it selected the most suitable of them.</seg>
<seg id="693">Correct selection of suppliers of small-scale contracts connected with the construction of a ring road with an estimated price of up to 500 thousand CZK</seg>
<seg id="694">It was not possible to verify the CZK, as the suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on the price and date of performance, but the documents of these negotiations were not prepared.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of tenders comply with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ with regard to the specific steps of the procedure and the choice of the individuals involved.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike in the Czech Republic, these steps of the procurement process in Germany are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross-principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the fairness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, in some cases of inspections, it was found that substantial steps in the process of verifying and evaluating tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the examination and evaluation of tenders allows for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">The inspections showed serious defects, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior appropriate screening and documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased monitoring of measures against the increased possibility of manipulation are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">In checking the legitimacy of the prices, the audited German contracting authorities did not in all cases use the full set of tools available and did not look at their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, weaknesses were found in the evaluation of the suitability of tenders and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">Following the examination and evaluation of tenders, the award process shall be concluded by the award of the contract or the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request its review where appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The deadline of 10 days applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of that period or before the outcome of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and upholds the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of the procurement right reviewed by an independent tribunal.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting entity will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by implementing procurement decisions quickly.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting entity shall adequately document the progress of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Identical or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries implemented the management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily depart from the results of a properly carried out verification and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within a specified period.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is due to the fact that, after this period, the tenderer is not bound by its tender.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers shall be informed of the outcome in good time, stating the reason why their tender has not been accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of the procurement procedure is admissible only if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in the tenders do not correspond to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period before the conclusion of a contract of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of the contract before a decision is taken on its EU provision and review award.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or only one tender meets the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, the contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender meets the conditions laid down in the tender dossier and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Key control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRHs</seg>
<seg id="735">The audits found few irregularities in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases of European proceedings, companies received empowerment letters before the notification period expired, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also in several cases of open procedures, the empowerment letters contained modifications incompatible with the content of the tender, e.g. new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting entities did not meet the time limits for the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because a bidder offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfil the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">During the reconstruction and construction of the university, in one case the contracting authority did not conclude a contract with the contractor for work in accordance with the draft contract contained in the bid of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some of the road repair and maintenance actions, the construction of the motorway and the ring road, the contracts were concluded later than provided for by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of building modifications in former military retreats, the contracting authority sent a notice of the selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers only after the statutory deadline.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the closure of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection of unsuccessful candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes the institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for contracting was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This may cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In future, contracting entities should eliminate such shortcomings when concluding a procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its different stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">Data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the fundamental requirement of the EU-wide principle of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision-making and justification guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Appropriate documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to provide detailed reasons for individual decisions and their merits significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In the case of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the EU Publications Office within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and this fulfils the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential details of its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission via the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics to provide an overview of the development of the single market in the construction sector.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Identical or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the provisions of the European Act on Documentation and Notification Obligations into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those mandatory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the limit of €25,000 (CZK 625,000) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15,000 (CZK 375,000) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only the parties are informed below that limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Key control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRHs</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of entries have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, such as the reasons for the delivery specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain the mandatory requirements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some of the required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="780">In some European procedures, the contracting authority erred in publishing a notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several awards, evidence of publication of the notice was lacking.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically examined files included the required minimum of information and were produced and sent in a timely manner.</seg>
<seg id="784">Prior transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, the contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the sponsor six months to spot the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not published during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant shortcomings were found in the documentation on the conduct of the procurement procedure, such as incorrect information on bid prices in the minutes of the evaluation committee meetings.</seg>
<seg id="792">Moreover, some of the documents opening the envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of repairs and maintenance of roads, motorway construction and ring roads, public procurement notices were sent after the deadline or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement and final selection procedures.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The audits revealed weaknesses substantially reducing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel audits of the SAO and the BRH were focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU with a view to creating a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Prevention measures aim not only to avoid or at least reduce corruption, but also to prevent financial damage and possible losses of confidence in the integrity of government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of both audit institutions - SAO and BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement law of both countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions give an internal view of common and different elements that can help both countries in further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">There is thus an important common basis in both countries for public procurement and the fulfilment of basic requirements in the areas of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting entities reinforce these requirements partly through very far-reaching measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended the provisions on public procurement requiring a European procedure to procedures below EU thresholds and is therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, inspections have shown that contracting entities do not always fully comply with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate these inconsistencies, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the audits identified risks affecting economy and achieving value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, the incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the public contract, which resulted in additional works, which were often awarded in breach of the law, the insufficient definition of the expected price, and the required qualifications, which narrow down the possible range of tenderers and thus reduce competition, particularly in the field of transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">Joint inspections did not aim to detect cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that the BRH and the SAO do not have sufficient tools for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they may examine whether the competent authorities of both countries take measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">As regards the prevention of corruption, the two countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions allow for broad and unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as a central element in the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations aim primarily at strengthening the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRHs</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles on the prevention of corruption that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been included in public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes very precisely, ways of complying with the requirements to prevent corruption during the procurement procedure and to select the persons included in it.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the BRH's view, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate tool to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in public procurement, while restricting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the cross-checking principle), transparency requirements, procurement documentation and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms for preventing corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions must comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas have highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting entities should provide further training to their employees in order to make them aware of anti-corruption requirements and to further raise their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the weaknesses revealed relates to activities delegated by the construction administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls on the delegation of powers increases the risk of abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic, anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level, which also significantly affect the area of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO audits took place in the period when one of the most important parts of the strategy was implemented, namely a significant change in the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of related implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The strategy adopted and the new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">According to the new regulations, the contracting authority must, for example, justify the effectiveness of the public contract, the determination of the expected value of the public contract, the adequacy of the requirements for qualification prerequisites, the establishment of the basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluating tenders, and duly document and publish everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, the SAO and the BRH have a favourable opinion of the ways of implementing EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their wide application in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency constitute an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model, established in the EU, can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential for material and non-material damage incurred as a result of manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, the BRH and the SAO insist that it is the responsibility of contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to the need for corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it has emerged that the proportion of open procurement procedures in the Czech Republic, which give room to competition and substantially reduce the possibility of corrupt behaviour, should increase.</seg>
<seg id="848">Procurement in instalments may also have a positive impact on the price obtained, where this is permissible and appropriate for the contracting entity. A higher number of bidders puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The organisation of the procurement procedure also has an impact on its progress.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organisations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contractual organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and the BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work where appropriate and to address it with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for guaranteeing that public contracts are awarded under a regime of well-functioning and honest competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
