<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="SRPOL">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel controls of excise tax administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint Final Report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The submitted joint report informs on the course and outcome of international cooperation in parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of both countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO of the Slovak Republic and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the performance of parallel audits focused on excise tax administration, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel controls was chosen on the basis of the fact that both EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to find out how it is applied at the national level, how the system of excise tax administration is set up and how the systems in Slovakia and the Czech Republic differ.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out consisted in the exchange of experience, the identification of differences and the identification of good practices.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, it was beneficial to note that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise administration is very limited without parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrik,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel inspections of SPD administration in Slovakia and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legal regulation of excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and their administration is in accordance with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences have been found between the regulation of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic.In the Czech Republic, verification of the economic stability of applicants for permits and mandatory marking and dyeing of selected mineral oils and some other oils contribute to the effective administration of excise duties.In the Slovak Republic, the distribution of stamps is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome for the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise tax evasion, the supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw materials, the implementation of the fuel distributor institute and the register of retailers of consumer packaging of alcohol have proven to be good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Excise tax revenues in Slovakia and the Czech Republic are growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's objectives of reducing labour taxation, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, among other things because there is no indexation of excise duty rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the importance of excise duties on total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, of reducing the tax burden on excise duties in real terms.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of environmental measures has been financially supported by the State in the long term, but these measures have a negative impact on excise revenues, which will therefore need to be replaced in the future by other revenues or by a reduction in state expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditure spent on the administration of excise duties in both the Czech Republic and Slovakia has been growing in the long term, mainly due to wage growth, and its effectiveness is declining.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the Slovak Republic, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditure on the computerisation of excise tax administration (IT expenditure) and expenditure on wages of employees performing permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses per alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">The e-administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic did not significantly affect the reduction of the number of tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend the SAO to reconsider the justification for the performance of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the effectiveness of administrative expenditure was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period that would have led to a reduction in the personnel demands of the excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative acts of tax administrators in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic was similar in the individual years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax subjects in the Slovak Republic is about one third lower than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical performance of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">Administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic is more administratively demanding than in the Czech Republic and more costly due to the ratio of the number of tax transactions to the number of entities.</seg>
<seg id="35">Electronic administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the administration of excise tax returns is fully computerized; in the Czech Republic, documents proving taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are transmitted electronically.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both methods of computerization support effective administration of excise taxes and therefore the SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend their application not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditure for the implementation of EMCS could not be compared as FS SR provided data on expenditure only for the upgrade of the system in 2011-2015, but expenditure was still incurred before this period.</seg>
<seg id="39">Expenditures spent in this period only on the upgrade of EMCS in Slovakia were approximately 20% higher than those spent in the Czech Republic both on the introduction of EMCS and on the upgrade of this system in more than ten years.</seg>
<seg id="40">Excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia did not achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when spending comparable expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of supervision is comparable in both countries, but in Slovakia the administration of excise duties is significantly more resource-intensive.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of the electronic system for monitoring the movement of products subject to excise duty (EMCS) made the administration of excise duties more efficient, but to a lesser extent in Slovakia, as significantly higher expenditures were spent on the implementation and modernisation of the system than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">The cooperation of the two audit institutions took place on the basis of the Cooperation Agreement in carrying out parallel inspections aimed at the administration of excise duties of 18. 8th 2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic agreed to carry out parallel audits, which will primarily focus on the issue of excise tax administration and the results of which will enable analysis, mutual comparison and evaluation of the established facts.</seg>
<seg id="46">Common audit issues were agreed on which parallel controls were based.</seg>
<seg id="47">Characteristics of the subject matter and objectives of the parallel control:</seg>
<seg id="48">The aim of the parallel checks was to compare the performance of excise administrations, taking into account qualitative and quantitative indicators, and to identify weaknesses in the excise administration process.</seg>
<seg id="49">In particular, the following main audit questions were to be answered:</seg>
<seg id="50">Did the excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when spending comparable expenses?</seg>
<seg id="51">Has the introduction of the Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS) made the administration of excise duties more efficient and has the expenditure to implement it been spent effectively?</seg>
