<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of a parallel audit of the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The 1977 Lima Declaration stresses that supreme audit institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenues to be controlled as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">Organisation The European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be one of the most important parts of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The 6th EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 dealt with the audit of public revenues carried out by SAI.</seg>
<seg id="7">The development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenue is an important step towards optimising the control activities of SAI.</seg>
<seg id="8">This applies in particular to taxation, which is the largest source of public revenue and the most prone to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may to some extent be unable to carry out control activities without the cooperation of the SAI of another state.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in the revenues of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In order to combat this crime, the competent authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">SAIs that carry out inspections in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">It was at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn that the idea of carrying out an audit of the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") and VIES was conceived in cooperation between the Supreme Audit Office and the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors).</seg>
<seg id="14">Careful preparation followed, when both parties first had to get acquainted with the legal environment and procedures for VAT administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of control topics was made and included in the control programme.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving efficient and efficient VAT administration is a long-term problem and individual countries (particularly the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify and make the collection of this tax more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrations, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the international information exchange system.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Inspection number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Administration of value added tax after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the auditing operation in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in administering value added tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "EU") connected with the free movement of goods and services and to examine the use of the VIES system, especially when controlling the application of the right to exemption from value added tax for intra-Community supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of control of intra-Community value added tax, with a special focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">This should result in a report on the weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">Value added tax information exchange system The audit operations were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the SAO") and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as "BRH") in mutual cooperation on the basis of a contract concluded between the two audit institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected business transactions carried out between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "Czech Republic") and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as the "German Republic"), the use of information obtained in the form of international cooperation between tax administrations and the comparison of VAT administration systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with the European Directive No.31 for the implementation of INTOSAI auditing standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from 1. 5. 2004 to 31. 12. 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">A parallel audit in the area of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the main point - the exchange of information on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 - the audit covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and recapitulative statements, which are closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit included the legal situation in the field of international passenger transport by bus and a comparison of certain statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">A comparison of the VAT administration systems of the two countries revealed differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion for registration is (among others) exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, payers are assigned only one tax identification number, which they also use in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, taxpayers are assigned a tax number when registering for VAT, which is used only for business transactions on the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If the German payer intends to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different registration methods create problems, conditions should be levelled across the EU (cf. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus transport of passengers.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus passenger transport is exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, the part of the transport which takes place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">Efforts should be made at EU level to harmonise the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of VAT (cf. 4.2.</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic payers file VAT returns only for individual tax periods (month or quarter), in Germany payers are obliged to file so-called provisional VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year they must file an annual VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike in the Czech Republic, payers in Germany are obliged to file provisional tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of the obligation to file VAT returns electronically in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see No. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While in the Czech Republic payers file summary reports at tax offices, in Germany payers file summary reports at CLO.</seg>
<seg id="53">Financial authorities in the Czech Republic therefore have data from summary reports immediately after their submission.</seg>
<seg id="54">The information from the recapitulative statements is available to the German tax authorities only after it has been processed at the CLO.</seg>
<seg id="55">The fight against VAT fraud requires that updated information on intra-Community transactions be made available as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="56">The monthly reporting of recapitulative statements would shorten the time lag between the transaction date and the update of the VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="57">This would in turn allow timely verification of taxation in the Member State of the purchaser (cf. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="58">However, this would require all Member States to adopt the same deadline for submitting a recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="59">(5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="60">The Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month deadline for incoming requests for information.</seg>
<seg id="61">The German CLO does not keep track of the elapsed time.</seg>
<seg id="62">Consequently, the German tax authorities dealt with a significantly lower percentage of applications received within the prescribed period.</seg>
<seg id="63">Due to these problems, the BRH recommended to the German CLO the implementation of a permanent warning (cf. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="64">(6) Risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="65">Each of the two Member States is developing its own risk management system (RMS), which has its own strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="66">The SAO and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="67">Successful RMS criteria, components and approaches must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State, otherwise fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5. ).</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the cooperation, both SAIs examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions between tax entities from the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="69">Together, thirty-one cases of commercial transactions in which there were doubts about their implementation or suspicions of VAT evasion were examined using the Customs Duty legislation.</seg>
<seg id="70">It was found that:</seg>
<seg id="71">In some cases, the tax authorities used the information obtained in the form of international cooperation and assessed the VAT liability of the payers.</seg>
<seg id="72">In these cases, the payers either improperly exercised the right to exemption of the supply from VAT or did not declare the acquisition of the goods in the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="73">In some cases, the tax authorities could not use the information obtained because the information was either incomplete or incomprehensible.</seg>
<seg id="74">In other cases, the information could not be used due to different legal provisions in both Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to respond to a request for information.</seg>
<seg id="76">Cases were found where payers erroneously reported business transactions in recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="77">As a result, the VIES data were incorrect and the tax administrations had to examine these cases (cf. 6th ).</seg>
