<seg id="175">- warning message - is sent if the transport of goods is assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="176">When evaluating the risk level of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database to send a warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data contained in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">In case the data in the SEED database does not match the data in the accompanying document (e.g. the registration number of the consignee of the goods or the registered office of the consignee does not match), ELO SR draws up a warning message which it sends to the ELO office of the consignee's Member State.</seg>
<seg id="178">In drawing up the reports, the ELO is governed by the regulations of the Taxation and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457, which determine, inter alia, the type and quantity of goods in the relevant units of measurement for drawing up the information and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">In the audited period of ELO SR, ELO CR sent one warning message.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information on commenced shipments of products exceeding the specified limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database during transport approval.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates the consignment as risky on the basis of its own analysis, it prepares a so-called warning message, which it sends to the relevant Member State through ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005 ELO CR sent two warning reports to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">The ISA - the system for controlling the movement of goods - makes it possible, by means of ISA applications, to control individual movements of excise products as well as the control of a specified route of transport between the operators mentioned in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information takes place on the basis of a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system shall be used in particular in cases where the consignor accepts the certified copy No 3 of the movement document and requests, for example, a refund of excise duty, and in cases where the information contained in the movement document cannot be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="186">In the audited period ELO SR sent 33 ISA applications to ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO CR sent 25 ISA requests to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="188">Customs authorities in the Czech Republic most often checked the data contained in the accompanying documents, in particular the quantity of products received or dispatched or whether the consignor of the products listed in the accompanying document was entitled to dispose of products subject to excise duty if this fact could not be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="189">The ISA application received was forwarded in both countries to the customs offices with territorial jurisdiction for the consignee or consignor of the products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="190">The customs authorities examined the data requested and communicated the outcome of the investigation via ELO to the other Member State.</seg>
<seg id="191">6th Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation of the SAO-Czech Republic and the SAO SR made it possible to compare the basic legislation governing the area of excise duties in both countries, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the initiation and termination of the transport of products under the conditional exemption regime between both countries, the records of these transports and to compare the exchange of information between customs authorities within the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 Comparing the legislation governing excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the following differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="194">(a) the procedure followed by tax entities and tax authorities when commencing the transport of products under a duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="195">Transport of products under the conditional exemption regime may be initiated by a tax subject in the Czech Republic only with the consent of the tax administrator, who will authorise the start of transport on condition that the transported products have been provided with tax security in the amount of the tax applicable to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The commencement of transport of products under the conditional exemption scheme in the Slovak Republic is not subject to the authorisation of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the tax subject was obliged to notify the tax administrator of the start of transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">He could start transporting mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, amendments to all Acts on Excise Duties were gradually adopted in Slovakia, according to which the consignor of goods under the duty suspension regime is obliged to send a copy of Copy No. 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office competent locally for the consignor prior to the start of transport;</seg>
<seg id="200">(b) within the time limits for sending copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The consignee in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copies no. 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification no later than the following working day after completion of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">Certified copy No. 3 must be sent to the sender no later than the next working day after receiving it from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in Slovakia is obliged to send the consignor of the products copy no. 3 confirmed by the tax administrator and the recipient of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in Slovakia and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of shipments of products under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and method of keeping such records are not regulated by legislation in the Czech Republic or Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="206">Customs authorities in both countries enter in the register all data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">For the monitoring of the movement of goods under suspension of excise duty between the Member States of the European Union, there is currently no single electronic system allowing excise authorities in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the movement of goods.</seg>
<seg id="208">Pursuant to Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003, an electronic system for monitoring the movement of excise products is foreseen from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of an agreement on cooperation in control activities, the Czech side handed over to the Slovak side a database of shipments of products under the duty suspension regime started in Slovakia and ended in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5 876 items concerning transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side provided the Czech side with a database of shipments of products under suspension of duty initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3 319 items concerning transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared data on transports listed in the register of commenced transports in the Czech Republic with the register of transports terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared data on transports of goods under suspension of tax initiated in Slovakia and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">Comparability of the data was hampered by the fact that the quantities of goods transported were not reported uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to clearly attribute data on individual movements in both registers, the accompanying documents were checked and no infringements of the suspension scheme or cases of tax evasion were detected.</seg>
<seg id="217">On the basis of the findings of parallel controls, it can be concluded that Member States can obtain valuable information from the transport register for improving the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the movement and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow the electronic transmission of the movement document and more effective control of movements under suspension of excise duty within the territory of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="220">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
