<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="SRPOL">
<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of value added tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxation is generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">So it goes without saying that the Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example is value added tax (VAT) fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">They are estimated to lose €100 billion each year in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">As early as 2005, the participants of the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">Within the framework of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for supervisory cooperation as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SAO") and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, also referred to as "BRH") carried out the first parallel audit operation in the field of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not confined to a single country but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps being taken to address this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a parallel follow-up.</seg>
<seg id="15">1st Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of value added tax (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (ex-post audit)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the auditing operation was to examine the procedures of the financial authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany") and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The auditing operation was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to be compared with identified good practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period covered the years 2006 to 2008, in case of relevant connections also the preceding and following periods until the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2nd Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">Subsequent inspection of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">Suspected cases of intra-community transactions have been identified during previous parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further screening.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations concerning VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up action carried out served to evaluate the actions taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused on selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in recovering receivables and VAT inspections of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the audit of VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors reached the following audit findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1st Recommendations from previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Payer registration conditions should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel inspections, a comparison of VAT registration systems in both countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different registration methods cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for the registration of payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation was presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including a database of VAT identification numbers.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also amended common standards for the registration and deregistration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAIs expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of the document agreed by the EU Member States in the framework of ECOFIN no longer contains this issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to regard this intention as a relevant preventive tool in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="44">In the framework of international cooperation, the previous follow-up action recommended that all EU Member States introduce a monthly deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements in order to allow for an earlier examination of the values of intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion connected with intra-Community transactions reduces the period for submitting recapitulative statements on intra-EU transactions to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit monthly recapitulative statements was not introduced within the deadline in line with the applicable EU rules, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany in order to improve the reliability of VIES data and to consider linking the two VAT return and recapitulative statements systems</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and the BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing successful risk management system criteria, components and approaches at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful risk management system criteria, components and approaches need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of fraudulent activities will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit revealed that our two Member States use different risk management systems, which have their strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO performed an audit of the EUROCANET system, which enables the exchange of information within the EU, while the BRH focused on the German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2nd Follow-up of selected cases of intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous auditing operation, business transactions were jointly scrutinized where there were doubts about their realization or discrepancies in the reporting of business transactions in tax returns or summary reports by taxpayers from both countries.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAIs selected for follow-up nine cases involving intra-community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The inspections carried out by the tax authorities of the countries concerned had not been concluded by the date of completion of our previous joint inspection operation.</seg>
<seg id="60">The subsequent auditing operation verified that most of the tax proceedings in connection with the above-mentioned selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany were concluded and that adequate measures were taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional assessments of VAT or prevention of refund of input tax).</seg>
<seg id="61">3rd Control of selected cases of risky intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-community transactions carried out by EU payers and included in EUROCANET were selected for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is a tool for detecting risky taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States" participation in the scheme is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active scheme member if some Member States refuse active participation.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration was not involved in the EUROCANET data exchange, it was not possible to obtain any information on which suppliers with German VAT ID were assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the auditing operation, the SAO found cases of common business transactions as well as cases with suspected involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent conduct concerning VAT.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax administrations have limited possibilities to control risky transactions, in particular as regards so-called missing traders, while the mere physical examination of documents can hardly prove any fraudulent conduct to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation arises for tax administrations when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-Community carousel trades.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be advisable to ensure greater cooperation between customs and tax authorities in order to identify goods and inconsistencies in the transport documentation, as well as to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is reluctant to participate actively in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are used to detect risky taxpayers, which have so far worked well for the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">There is a need for communication and exchange of experience between EU Member States in this area.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU reached political agreement on a draft regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far from the use of EUROCANET should feed into the creation of this new network to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4th Mutual assistance in debt recovery</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international recovery assistance, all EU Member States are governed by the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the method of processing requests for international assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic and Germany is the same.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and the BRH compared statistics submitted by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs consider it useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent mismatches.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, SAIs agree that reliable statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to carry out an analysis on the basis of more detailed statistics to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the view of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with low recovery rates to increase recovery rates to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should be actively involved in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">The SAIs analysed the legal situation regarding VAT control of large tax entities (hereinafter also referred to as "VDS") in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from tax administrations in the form of a questionnaire on areas considered by SAI to be essential for the management of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">It is clear from the responses received that the situation in both countries is developing differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system for guiding the selection of risk-prone cases based on a large volume of relevant data (e.g. information from tax audits, data from balance sheets and profit and loss accounts, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures effective management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">A dedicated financial authority for the management of VDS is planned to be established in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">In Germany, a similar system does not yet exist, which makes it difficult to manage and analyse VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">To date, Germany has concentrated more on the selection of the individual cases in question, in particular on the basis of data from the VAT return and the recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of these data relies on different components of risk management, which will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3rd Progress of control action</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Progress of the auditing operation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">The auditing operation was performed from May 2009 to February 2010 by Department II. - the separation of State budget revenues and territorial departments IX. Plzen, X. České Budějovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="102">The audited bodies were: Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "Czech Ministry of Finance") and 25 financial authorities (hereinafter referred to as the "FÚ"): FÚ Brno II, FÚ Brno III, FÚ Brno IV, FÚ in Břeclav, FÚ in Domažlice, FÚ in Hodonín, FÚ in Hradec Králové, FÚ in Cheb, FÚ in Jablonec nad Nisou, FÚ in Karlovy Vary, FÚ in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FÚ in Kraslice, FÚ ÚT Ostrava I, FÚm Ostrava III, FÚT in Píkov, FÚ in Píkov</seg>
<seg id="103">The audit conclusion of this auditing operation was approved by the College of the Supreme Audit Office on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Conduct of the audit operation in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit was carried out between February 2009 and February 2010 by the Audit Service for Indirect Taxes and the staff of the designated regional audit offices in Berlin, Frankfurt am Main and Munich.</seg>
<seg id="106">Following the selection of a sample of cases, a number of Länder were informed of the mission of the monitoring operation.</seg>
<seg id="107">In addition to the interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance, an audit mission was carried out in the following Länder: • Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hesse, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax files of the following tax authorities were included: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München (Central Tax Office in Munich), Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord (Hamburg-North), Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg für Großunternehmen (Hamburg-VDS);</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, discussions were held with the Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd (Halle-South) and with the financial directorates in Frankfurt am Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">A report on the audit findings was submitted to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two audit institutions</seg>
<seg id="112">In preparation for parallel audit actions, a meeting of representatives of both audit institutions took place in September 2008 to discuss and define the topics of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="113">Finally, in December 2008, the highest representatives of the two SAIs signed an agreement on cooperation in carrying out parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="114">At the meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the control teams informed each other of the initial results achieved during the preparation of the control, discussed possible audit approaches and agreed on the way forward.</seg>
<seg id="115">The second meeting took place in Prague on 2. - 4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The review teams exchanged the findings accumulated so far and agreed on a timetable for drawing up the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="117">In carrying out parallel audits, both SAIs decided to focus on: • follow-up of the implementation of the recommendations made in the previous report, • review of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were not resolved during the previous parallel audit, • review of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were classified as high-risk cases, • review of the procedure of tax administrations in the area of international assistance in recovering VAT receivables, • tax audits of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">A report on the results of the parallel control actions was prepared during a workshop in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4th Control of VAT administration in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Evaluation of the recommendations of the previous audit</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Evaluation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Payer registration conditions should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">Based on the results of the previous auditing operation, the SAO recommended modifying the conditions for VAT registration and introducing a new rule for deregistration in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">The revised conditions should make it possible to reduce the risk of possible VAT evasion more effectively.</seg>
<seg id="126">In this context, it was found that in some cases the tax authorities did not use the right to cancel the VAT registration of payers who did not comply with obligations arising from Act No.235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Act").</seg>
<seg id="127">The Czech Ministry of Finance has not yet proposed a change to the provision consisting in introducing an obligation for tax administrators to cancel VAT registration for payers in case of repeated failure to submit a VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="128">According to the VAT Act, the tax administrator may cancel the registration of the tax payer ex officio in cases where: a) the payer has not made a transaction to the tax administrator for twelve consecutive months without announcing the reason, b) the payer fails to fulfil his obligations under this Act, c) the payer ceases to be a taxable person.</seg>
<seg id="129">In the previous auditing operation, it was found that the applicable legislation allowed the FVO for Prague 1 to cancel VAT registration as of 31 January of the following calendar year to so-called non-established payers who did not incur any obligation to declare and pay tax during the current calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="130">The FVO for Prague 1 often did not cancel VAT registration for these payers, as the relevant provision set an insufficient deadline for deregistration.</seg>
<seg id="131">This problem was eliminated by an amendment to the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2009.</seg>
<seg id="132">The tax administrator is entitled to cancel the registration of a non-established tax payer if the tax payer did not supply any goods or services subject to tax or exempt goods or services with the right to deduct VAT in the previous calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="133">Recommendation 2</seg>
<seg id="134">Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="135">In the framework of international cooperation, the previous follow-up action recommended that all EU countries introduce a monthly deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="136">The Council Directive reduces the period for submitting recapitulative statements on intra-EU transactions to one month. This measure was implemented in the Czech Republic through the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="137">There is also a new obligation to submit summary reports in electronic form.</seg>
<seg id="138">The summary report must be submitted by the payer even if the services for which the place of performance is determined pursuant to Section 9 para. 1 of the VAT Act, supplied to another Member State to a person registered for tax purposes in another Member State and where the recipient of such services is obliged to declare and pay the tax.</seg>
<seg id="139">This obligation is based on Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of supply of services.</seg>
<seg id="140">Recommendation 3</seg>
<seg id="141">Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in order to improve the reliability of VIES data This recommendation concerned the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="142">The Czech administration performs the comparison of data on intra-Community transactions reported in VAT tax returns and summary reports of Czech payers automatically in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="143">Recommendation 4</seg>
<seg id="144">Sharing successful risk management system criteria, components and approaches at EU level</seg>
<seg id="145">Proper collection of VAT is one of the prerequisites for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.</seg>
<seg id="146">The fight against VAT fraud is therefore a priority area and has received considerable attention in recent years.</seg>
<seg id="147">The importance of this fight is evidenced, inter alia, by the conclusions of a study published by the European Commission in October 2009, in which an external evaluator attempted to establish the difference between the eligible and actually collected levels of VAT in the 25 EU Member States (EU-25) during the period 2000-2006.</seg>
<seg id="148">On the basis of an analysis of the available data, the author of the analysis concludes that the estimated loss of uncollected VAT over this period is between EUR 90 and 113 billion, with an average of 12% of eligible VAT not collected annually in the EU-25.</seg>
<seg id="149">For the Czech Republic, the VAT loss for 2006 was even estimated at 18%.</seg>
<seg id="150">In the framework of international cooperation, a previous follow-up exercise noted that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="151">The successful criteria, components and approaches of this system must be shared and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="152">As regards the risk management system, the SAO performed an audit of the EUROCANET system for the exchange of information in the EU.</seg>
<seg id="153">Cases of risky intra-Community transactions carried out by EU taxpayers included in the EUROCANET system were selected for audit (see Chapter 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="154">The objectives of improving administrative cooperation and the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud should also be achieved through the establishment of the EUROFISC network, which should improve the cooperation of the responsible authorities in a way that allows fraud to be detected from the outset.</seg>
<seg id="155">This network should later become an important source of information for the risk assessment of intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="156">The ECOFIN Council already approved the creation of EUROFISC on 7 October 200812, while setting out the basic principles governing the network.</seg>
<seg id="157">EUROFISC is modelled on the EUROCANET rapid and selective information exchange system already in place, developed by the Belgian tax administration in cooperation with other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF.</seg>
<seg id="158">The aim of this system is to detect risky commercial transactions and entities involved in organised VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="159">4.1.2 Evaluation of the recommendations in Germany</seg>
<seg id="160">The evaluation of the recommendations of the first report led to the following findings:</seg>
