<seg id="281">Since the 1st quarter of 2008, the Czech Republic has been sending data on risky transactions and tax entities acting as suppliers to EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="282">Within the framework of international cooperation, nine Czech tax entities included in the EUROCANET system were selected for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="283">These operators acted either as suppliers or as purchasers of goods.</seg>
<seg id="284">Relevant data from tax administrations from other Member States were captured in EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="285">As the German tax administration was not involved in the EUROCANET data exchange, it was not possible to obtain any information that would help to establish whether suppliers with a German VAT ID were assessed by the German tax administration as risky entities.</seg>
<seg id="286">The auditing operation revealed cases of routine commercial transactions as well as cases of suspected involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent VAT-related conduct.</seg>
<seg id="287">Where relevant, tax administrations have used the exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="288">For example:</seg>
<seg id="289">• Tax administrations did not reveal any suspicions of involvement in risky transactions when verifying signal information.</seg>
<seg id="290">The tax authorities continuously monitor such tax entities for inclusion in EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="291">• During the verification of risky transactions, the tax authorities did not show deviations from the rules applicable to the calculation of the tax and VAT bases in the accounting records submitted, despite finding irregularities in the transport and storage of goods or uncovering business relationships with suspect or non-contact companies from other Member States.</seg>
<seg id="292">• Verification of commercial transactions was complicated as some taxpayers did not cooperate with tax authorities and could not be contacted.</seg>
<seg id="293">The locally competent tax authorities mostly examined risky tax entities and risky transactions identified in the EUROCANET signal information.</seg>
<seg id="294">Tax administrations have limited possibilities when examining risky transactions, in particular in relation to the examination of missing traders , and only a physical check of documents makes it difficult to prove fraudulent conduct to the tax subject.</seg>
<seg id="295">Stricter VAT registration requirements and more flexible deregistration would help reduce missing trader fraud.</seg>
<seg id="296">In the case of tax subjects involved in carousel fraud and other fraudulent activities, VAT registration takes place for the purpose of reporting fictitious supplies of goods within the EU or for the purpose of issuing formally correct tax documents to payers who improperly deduct input VAT on the basis of them.</seg>
