<seg id="590">• which have not been used to carry out any economic activity pursuant to § 72 para. 1 of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which have been used for representation pursuant to § 75 para. 3 of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">• on the basis of tax documents that did not meet the requirements set out in Section 73 para. 1 of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- VDS did not declare output VAT pursuant to Section 21 para. 1 of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It has been noted that there are no rules at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It follows that uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection services do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="596">VAT findings are not separately recorded by the Länder in so far as they result from VDS tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the ZAUBER database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder have to enter their assessed increased tax (VAT) liability if it exceeds a certain amount, the Federal Central Revenue Office is able to analyse this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration carry out analyses of areas of control that give rise to a high "revenue" and draw consequences for management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they are launching nationwide audits focused on risky commodities or on the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection services do not provide data on audit areas that generate high "revenue."</seg>
<seg id="602">There are different views on the analysis process as well as on the materiality management of cases.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax authorities provide special information, but its use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">Differences in the replies of both Member States show that the Czech Republic ensures a system that collects a wealth of data from tax audits carried out, as well as data from financial statements - balance sheets and profit and loss accounts.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-prone cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, it is planned to establish a specialised financial authority in the Czech Republic for the management of VDS.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax authorities do not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">This makes it more difficult to carry out these tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places greater emphasis on the selection of individual cases on the basis of data from the submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that Member States should be able to ensure adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help to reduce VAT gaps.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the revenue from VAT collection will increase and the rate of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of both SAIs on parallel audits of VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">Both SAIs have gained a better understanding of each other's systems in the following areas: • intra-Community transactions; • VAT risk management, in particular as regards the selection of risk-prone transactions; • assistance with the recovery of VAT claims; and • VAT control for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud detection strategies as well as differences in the above-mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The control findings were compared and good practices were identified.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, the two SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to launch a debate on approaches and strategies within the Member States, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of both SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT administration.</seg>
